`from(iterable)` accepts both sync and async iterables. Each yielded value becomes a `next` emission; the observable completes when the iterator is exhausted.

```typescript
import { from, Observable } from "rxjs";

async function* pages(): AsyncIterable<number> {
  yield 1;
  yield 2;
  yield 3;
}

export const page$: Observable<number> = from(pages());

page$.subscribe((p: number) => {
  void p;
});
```

`from(promise)` emits the resolved value and then completes. If the promise rejects, the Observable errors with the rejection reason — no silent swallow. This means error-handling operators like `retry` and `catchError` compose naturally.

```typescript
import { from, Observable, retry, timer } from "rxjs";

interface Price {
  usd: number;
}

declare function fetchPrice(): Promise<Price>;

export const price$: Observable<Price> = from(fetchPrice()).pipe(
  retry({ count: 3, delay: (_err, n) => timer(2 ** n * 100) })
);
```

